STATE OF NEBRASKA OFFICE OF THE AUDITOR OF PUBLIC ACCOUNTS Lincoln, Nebraska, December 1, 1912. tHis Excellency, Chester H. Aldrich, Governor of the State of Ne - braska: Dear Governor — In accordance with the statutes relating to the report of this department, we take pleasure in submitting our biennial re- r, covering the period from November 30, 1910, to November 30, 1912. We respectfully direct your attention to the tabular statements which Ke a detailed statement of the receipts and disbursements during this iod, and point out exact financial condition of the several departments under our state government. In our report of two years ago, we recommended legislation which Eild improve the condition of our state, and make more effective our eral departmenis in service for the people. This legislation, of neces - ', centered more power in the Auditor's department, and the argu- ment was effectively used that we desired to take unto ourselves the powers of a czar. It must be remembered that any supervising official must have power to correct bad conditions, and it goes without saying that the intimate acquaintance the State Auditor necessarily has with the conditions of which this proposed legislation treated, should entitle his recommendations in this line to weight, not only with the Governor, who is about to recommend laws, but with the legislator who is proposing » enact laws for the advancement of the public welfare. The total estimated income for the next biennial period, commencing Eil 1, 1913, and ending March 31, 1915, is $5,315,168.22. Against this •unt are the estimates from the several departments and state insti - ons, amounting to $5,098,699.74, which would leave a balance of $216,468.48. The interest on this fund for the last biennial period amounted to iur statement of the school funds shows interest in Permanent school fund $8,480,355 35 Permanent university fund 213,079 44 Agricultural college endowment fund 540,352 71 Normal endowment fund 74,200 00 Total 19,307,987 50 9,307,987 5i

6 tWe have had an audit made of the several state institutions and in one instance was a shortage found. A portion of our recommenda - s were adopted by the last legislature and, as a consequence, all the receipts are remitted direct to the state treasury. While a special amount of cash is kept on hand at the institutions, yet when any of this is ex - pended, it is vouchered and returned to the fund. By this method a voucher is furnished for every dollar of state money expended and the voucher can be found in this office. We audit the university semi-annu - ff and are pleased to report a most careful expenditure of the funds well as an exact accounting of the disbursements. Believing that the people of this state who send their boys and girls to this institution want the very best instruction that can be secured, even if the cost is greater, we would suggest that it might be worthy the attention of the legislative committee, whose duty it will be to in - spect this institution, to note the days absent of the high salaried professors and the number of students paid for teaching the several classes. As per our recommendation of two years ago, the private school of music has been divorced from the state university. A very satisfactory system of accounting has been installed in the state penitentiary and also in the four normal schools. I have no doubt that the Board of Control will appreciate the necessity of a uniform system and periodical reports throughout all the institutions During the biennial period, the bond department has approved and registered 377 issues of bonds, amounting to $4,716,136.39, distributed as follows: County bonds — 11 issues — J710.000.00; precinct bonds — 8 issues — $59,000.00; city, village and drainage district bonds — 151 issues — $1,697, - 582.39; school district bonds — 207 issues — $2,249,554.00. Many issues have also been rejected. For the first time since this department was insti - tuted, the records have been completed, showing the cancellation of all bonds which have been paid. To complete the record of the cancellation of registered bonds has entailed considerable labor and persistence on the part of this department. The necessary information could only be obtained by correspondence with the proper authorities in the several counties and towns. As far back as the year 1875 no report of bonds paid had been made to the office. There being no provision in our laws for reporting the payment of bonds, except counties and precincts, we would recommend that a law be enacted providing that a report be sent to this department showing all bonds paid and the time thereof. A bill will also be introduced providing that bonds of every description be registered with the department. Under our present laws the bonds of Omaha, South Omaha and Lincoln, with the exception of school bonds, are not regis - tered here. Nebraska bonds sell readily, not only in this state but in the eastern markets, and representatives of large companies from different parts of the United States have informed us that bonds registered in this office sell to excellent advantage. Consequently, were all bonds regis - te v d, it would more than compensate for the extra amount of work such a change would entail.

7 The statutes now provide that the Governor may designate some bank in the city of New York as the state agency for the payment of bonds and coupons issued by the state or any county, township, precinct city or school district, and before making the appointment he shall re - quire a bond of double the amount of money which said agency may have in its custody, said bond to be approved by the Governor, Auditor ot State and Secretary of State. Up*S) investigation, I find that this law has been ignored for many years, but, without appointment or the Tiling of a bond, the Kountze Brothers of Not York have h*M acting as the fiscal agency of Nebraska; that this law also provides that one performing this rice is entitled to charge a commission of not to exceed one-eighth of per cent. tin this enlightened age of the world it is remarkable that the people Nebraska would keep on deposit in New York one-half million dollars, more, and pay some one one-eighth of one per cent to care for the money. I most heartily concur with the State Treasurer in his recom - mendation that the law be amended, naming the State Treasurer as the State Fiscal Agent. He is under a million dollar bond and this fund, rtead of being in New York, will be deposited in Nebraska, earning two three per cent on daily balances. tThe county treasurer examiners have brought the examinations down a period of less than eighteen months. It has been our ambition to ng these examinations down to an annual audit, but it was impossible accomplish more than we have done. The Insurance Department is one of the big departments. The reve - nue in fees and taxes for 1911 was $127,871.73, and in 1912, $139,090.31, or a total for the biennium of $266,962.04, thus furnishing revenue to the state of one-quarter million dollars. The people of Nebraska expended for in - surance in 1911, $13,823,436.00 and received in claims paid, $6,644,477.00. This proves, beyond question, that It is one of the big interests ot Ne - braska and our legislation should be of such a character as to foster and build these institutions in our own state, giving to the managements of companies encouragement and general approval of the business done, but. at the expense of the policy holder; they should not prosper by dishonest methods, simply because they are home companies. Both the republican and democratic parties have pledged the people of this state remedial insurance legislation, and, if platform promises are promises to be fulfilled, each member of the legislature is bound by his party promise to lend his assistance to the passage of bills which will give to the policy holder and purchaser the things that belong to him, and to safeguard his contract by law rather than leave that important duty to the management of the companies. We recommend that a bill be passed governing stock selling schemes, usually termed a "Blue Sky" law. At the present time there is no vested power to control this condition and we believe that in selling insurance stock the proposed plan should be laid before the Insurance Department

8 this stock should be required to have a license. If a banking, building and loan or miscellaneous stock selling scheme, then it should be brought before the Banking Board for its approval. There is no law permitting the change of a mutual company to a stock basis and yet the history of this and other states is replete with changes of this character. Much criticism has been heaped upon the de - partments and the management of stock companies. In order that the position of this state may be made clear and that the equites of the policy holders will be protected in transactions of this character, we would rec - ommend a law clearly denning the steps necessary to take, to make these transformations. The proxy system, in mutual companies, is a most complex one with which to deal; proxies are provided for in the constitution of the state and to do away with this system would necessitate a constitutional amend - ment. The system makes an oligarchy and the intention of a mutual company is clearly a democracy. Many policy holders have learned by ex - perience how one or two officers can secure the proxies and, even against the wishes of interested members, govern the affairs of an organization. The only method we can suggest, by which this condition can be over - come, is to compel companies by law to submit all changes in law, the names of the candidates for office and the fixing of salaries, to the mem - bers, permitting them to cast their ballot at their places of residence and, after a canvass of the votes received, the result should govern the company. We have at the present time many companies doing business in the state that are not admitted under the laws. A law should be passed com - pelling all companies to seek admission through the regular channels, so that if a policy holder is wronged, he can get service on the State Auditor instead of having to trace the company to another state to commence suit, and the company would then be compelled to make an annual show - ing of its receipts and disbursements. Estimates as to probable results of the settlement of a life Insurance policy are generally misrepresented! and it is bad business practice. We believe that if estimates are to be permitted in the sale of insurance, the president and secretary of the company should be compelled to sign the estimate and attach same to the policy, and our opinion is that estimates should be prohibited. We have had enough past experience in receiverships for insurance companies to convince us that it would be a public benefit to give the insurance department power to liquidate a company found in an insolvent condition, and we would recommend the passage of such a law. The reserve on a life insurance policy is a sum of money set aside to fulfill the contract; this is the policy holder's money paid in advance, and if, after a limited period not exceeding three years, at any time he should lapse the policy, this state, like other states, should compel the company to give him, automatically, value received in extended or paid up insur - ance for the value of the money he has on deposit with said company.

9 tWe would recommend a law compelling insurance companies to de - it securities to the value of their reserves, with the state. A letter ressed to the State Auditor of either Iowa or Missouri will convince you of the virtue of this law. The successful companies of these states es - tablish the fact that such a law is not injurious to the companies or a great expense to the state. With this law in effect the state will always have sufficient securities in her custody to reinsure the business of any company, thus insuring the policy holder against loss. The securities should all run to "the company and every possible safeguard against loss be given, to insure their safety. Under this plan the chance for loss to the companies would not be large as it is under existing laws. Se - curities in the custody of the state would be beyond the reach of any unscrupulous insurance official. We would also recommend that under r; existing conditions the bond of the Deputy Auditor, who has charge these reserves, be increased. I Fraternal societies are organized on the principle that the organiza - 1 belongs to its members. This being true it follows, in fairness, that ore an insurance contract which has been entered into by these so - cieties is changed or a reinsurance contract effected which changes their condition, that the subject matter should be submitted to the subordinate rges and each member be entitled to vote on the proposed legislation changes, and we recommend surh a law. It has been recommended in previous reports, and in our last biennial report that the Insurance Department should be separated from the Auditor's office. As we stated in our previous report, we are of the opinion this change would be beneficial if the tenure of office of the In - surance Commissioner could be made six years, and we would recommend that a new office be created and he be elected by the people. We are pleased to report that we have conducted the business of our several departments without creating deficiencies, and are of the opinion that the appropriations made are sufficient to enable the departments to do their best work. Sincerely trusting that our efforts will bear fruit, I am, most respect- SILAS R. BARTON. Auditor Public Accounts.

REPORT OF THE INSURANCE DEPARTMENT OF THE STATE OF NEBRASKA FOR THE BIENN1UM ENDING NOVEMBER 30, 1912

December 1, 1912. Hon. Silas R. Barton. Auditor of Public Accounts, Lincoln, Nebraska. Plir: I herewith transmit a statement of the business transacted by Insurance Department of the State of Nebraska for the biennium ending November 30, 1912; also a summary of the reports of the various companies lieensed to operate in this state, showing the business trans - acted by the companies and their financial condition as of December 31, 1911, with comparative statements for the years 1907, 1908, 1909 and 1910, also a list of companies admitted during the past two years and a list of those that have ceased doing business in this state during the
